{
  "answer": "In the *Gaṇapatitattva*, Īśvara instructs Gaṇapati on the Six-Limbed Yoga (*ṣaḍaṅga-yoga*), comprising withdrawal (*pratyāhāra*), meditation (*dhyāna*), breath-control (*prāṇāyāma*), concentration (*dhāraṇā*), contemplation (*tarka*), and absorption (*samādhi*). These disciplines purify the mind and lead toward union with Śiva, culminating in liberation as the supreme Śiva (*paramaśiva*) at the point twelve finger-widths above the crown, where the Void is proclaimed supreme.[^1][^2]\n\nThe text later references *yogic sleep* (*yoganidrā*) as a subtle practice for attaining transparency of the body and radiant consciousness, foundational to liberation.[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Gaṇapatitattva*, [Chapter 1 (translation)](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-1a44bb).\n[^2]: *Gaṇapatitattva*, [Chapter 1 (translation)](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-f36006).\n[^3]: *Gaṇapatitattva*, [Chapter 1 (translation)](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-5f9128).",
